\f1\b\fs32 \cf0 \ul \ulc0 About
\fs24 \

\f0\b0 \ulnone 	iTunesCheck is a program that I wrote after checking out several other programs and not finding exactly what I wanted. It provides global hot keys for controlling iTunes without switching to it, it provides a hotkeyable floating window that shows the currently playing song, and it provides a hotkey for quickly finding a song without switching to iTunes.\
\

\f1\b\fs32 \ul \
Installation
\fs24 \

\f0\b0 \ulnone 	Copy the iTunesCheck program to your favorite spot.\
	/Applications is nice if you don't have a favorite spot. :)\
\
\

\f1\b\fs32 \ul Upgrading
\fs24 \
	
\f0\b0 \ulnone You'll need to delete the following files, depending on which version you're upgrading from.
\f1\b \ul \
	
\f0\b0 \ulnone Before 0.85:\
		~/Library/Preferences/net.stormsilver.iTunesCheck.plist\

\f1\b \ul \
	
\f0\b0 \ulnone Before 0.5:\
		iTunesCheck (from wherever you put it when you installed it)\
		~/Library/PreferencePanes/SSNiTCheck.prefPane\
		~/Library/Preferences/net.stormsilver.iTCheck.plist\
\
	Since the program is still in a state of flux at this point, it might be a good idea to delete the preferences file every time you upgrade. You never know what oddities can be caused by bad prefs. In fact, if you're having trouble, you should delete the prefs file and see if it goes away before emailing me.\
\
\

\f1\b\fs32 \ul Usage
\f0\b0\fs24 \ulnone \
	Open iTunesCheck when you have it where you want it. The first time you run it, the preferences window will open. I tried to pick reasonable default values for everything, but feel free to customize them. (That's why they're preferences, after all) Be sure to note the hotkey for showing the preferences window (
\f1\b command-option-P
\f0\b0  by default).\
\
	To set the position of the floating window, click the "Set Position" button, and then drag the resulting window to where you want it. Click the "Set Position" button again when you're done to make the window go away.\
\
	Using fewer things in the display window will enhance performance. Adding shadows and bolding to different parts of the display will make it look really cool. :)\
\
	Typing something in the quick play window is exactly the same as typing it into the search field in iTunes. As you know, this will search song name, artist, and album... everything, really. The more specific you are about the song you want, the better. If your search returns multiple results, a selection window will come up. For really large result sets, it's really slow. :( You can select a specific playlist to search within. If you decide you just want to hear all the results, the "Playlist" button on the selection window will create a playlist called "QuickPlay" and start playing it.\
\
	Clicking on the info window will make it go away instantly. Useful if it's in your way.\
\
	If you think the info window is too big, just decrease the font size. Go to the preferences window, click "Setup Display", click "Font Panel", and then choose appropriate font sizes.\
