\f1\b\fs32 \ul Known Issues
\f0\b0\fs24 \ulnone \
	- Resetting to factory defaults won't set the hot keys properly the first time. Something to do with defaults caching. Just 		hit the button again once or twice.\
	- Don't position the info window with the origin (the lower-left corner) of the window off the screen (or on a screen that 		doesn't exist, if you have more than one display). The sizing will be very, very off.\
	\
	
\fs28 Notes:\
	
\fs20 (things that you might think are broken, but aren't, really)
\fs24 \
	- To listen to your iPod with quick play, you'll need to have it set to update songs 
\f1\b manually
\f0\b0 . The reason for this\
		is that iTunes won't let you play songs from it if it's set to update automatically. You'll still be able to see the\
		playlists on your iPod, and even search from them, but you can't play the songs. Thanks, Apple.\
	- To listen to a shared library with quick play, you have to first select it in iTunes so that iTunes will go grab\
		the songs and playlists in that library. (This only has to be done once.) The reason for this is because iTunes 		won't show the shared library as a viable source until it knows that it can play things from it. Unfortunately, this 		decreases the usefulness somewhat, but it's a limitation in iTunes that can't be overcome.\
	- You won't be able to click on anything if you set your window opacity to 0. Your clicks will just go straight through\
		the window you were trying to click in.\
	- Using the playlist feature of quick play won't work with anything other than tracks from your library, because iTunes\
		won't let you add iPod or shared tracks to a playlist. Thanks, Apple.\
